1. Business Idea¶

The problem is in regard to the architecture of the data storage and the goal is to improve the data solution that has the goal of executing critical data transfers between various parts of the companys data storage architecture. The analysis focuses on the ETL process within the structure presented in Graph 1.

Graph 1. ETL process

The target variable in project is binary variable job result which takes 0 for failed pipelines so our goal of the project is correct detection of the failed pipelines that is TP True Positive. The benchmark is the failure rate which equals 19.5% in historical data. Each failed pipeline means lost time and unnecessary costs.

The data was very limited, with the information solely on the time and cost of a single run of the pipeline as well as the amount of data processed in that run and its outcome - success or failure.

Dataset a dataset containing information about 2530 runs of the data pipeline described in the architecture diagram. In this dataset, we have the following columns:

  • seconds_processing The number of seconds that the ETL pipeline has taken to run.
  • MB_data_processed Amount of MB that have been processed during the pipeline execution
  • dollars_run_cost Total cost of running the pipeline for that specific run
  • job_result Result of the ETL process, either successful or failed. In cases that it failed, we can consider that the pipeline took all the specified time to run but for some problem during execution, it failed at the end, or the data was not transferred completely or accurately, in which case the pipeline run was of no use

2. Data science¶

This gives as a very narrow view of the problem - it is difficult to point out definitive causes of the failures, which account for 20% of the sample.

#Graph for continuous variables
def n_plot(df, feature_name, target_name, palettemap, hue_order, feature_scale): 
    df['Counts'] = "" 
    fig, [axis0,axis1] = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,5))
    sns.distplot(df[feature_name], ax=axis0);
    sns.violinplot(x=feature_name, y="Counts", hue=target_name, hue_order=hue_order, data=df,
                   palette=palettemap, split=True, orient='h', ax=axis1)
    axis1.set_xticks(feature_scale)
    plt.show()
    
#Graph for Categorical/Ordinal variables
def c_plot(df, feature_name, target_name, palettemap): 
    fig, [axis0,axis1] = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,5))
    df[feature_name].value_counts().plot.pie(autopct='%1.1f%%',ax=axis0)
    sns.countplot(x=feature_name, hue=target_name, data=df,
                  palette=palettemap,ax=axis1)
    plt.show()

    
palette = {0: "green", 1: "red"}

Table 1. Pearson Correlation of Features

  • All the features are highly correlated with each other. The highest correlation (0.85) is present between pln_run_cost and seconds_processing variables (which is intuitive) -> the longer the processing time the higher the cost of using the Azure services.

  • Other variables also have high correlations, but lower than (0.75). The amount of data processed also increases the total cost.

  • Since possible multicollinearity problem we transform variables into categorical variables.

It is worth noting that taking into account all the variables is usually not the best way to get a good result in the ML approach.Correlation testing is not sufficient to expertly decide which variable to discard and which to keep in the model.

3.7. Performing a selection of variables

We use the next technics to select features: 

    1. Variance Threshold 
    2. Univariate feature selection 
    3. Recursive feature elimination 
    4. SelectFromModel 
    5. Feature importance

1. Variance Threshold: this is the removal of variables whose variance does not reach a certain threshold.

In [554]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import VarianceThreshold

mdlsel = VarianceThreshold(threshold=0.1)
mdlsel.fit(dfd)
ix = mdlsel.get_support()

df_VT = pd.DataFrame(mdlsel.transform(dfd), columns = dfd.columns.values[ix])
selected_VT = dfd.columns.values[ix]
print(selected_VT)

['job_result' 'small_GB' 'medium_GB' 'small_PLN' 'medium_PLN' 'small_SEC'
 'medium_SEC' 'high_SEC']

2. Univariate: selects the best variables based on one-dimensional statistical tests.

In [555]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import chi2

X = dfd.drop('job_result',axis=1)
y = dfd['job_result']

mdlsel = SelectKBest(chi2, k=8) 
mdlsel.fit(X,y)
ix = mdlsel.get_support() 
df_SB = pd.DataFrame(mdlsel.transform(X), columns = X.columns.values[ix]) 
selected_SB = X.columns.values[ix]
print(selected_SB)

['small_GB' 'medium_GB' 'high_GB' 'small_PLN' 'medium_PLN' 'high_PLN'
 'small_SEC' 'high_SEC']
In [556]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import GenericUnivariateSelect
X = dfd.drop('job_result',axis=1)
y = dfd['job_result']
transformer = GenericUnivariateSelect(chi2, 'k_best', param=8)
transformer.fit(X,y)
ix = transformer.get_support()
df_GUS = pd.DataFrame(transformer.transform(X), columns = X.columns.values[ix])
selected_GUS = X.columns.values[ix]
print(selected_GUS)

['small_GB' 'medium_GB' 'high_GB' 'small_PLN' 'medium_PLN' 'high_PLN'
 'small_SEC' 'high_SEC']

3. Recursive feature elimination given an external estimator that assigns weights to features (e.g., coefficients of a linear model), recursive feature elimination (RFE) is the selection of features by recursively considering smaller and smaller sets of features.

In [557]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
linmdl = LogisticRegression()
X = dfd.drop('job_result',axis=1)
y = dfd['job_result']
mdl = RFE(linmdl,n_features_to_select=8)
mdl.fit(X,y)
ix = mdl.get_support() 
df_RFE = pd.DataFrame(mdl.transform(X), columns = X.columns.values[ix]) 
selected_RFE = X.columns.values[ix]
print(selected_RFE)

['small_GB' 'medium_GB' 'high_GB' 'small_PLN' 'high_PLN' 'small_SEC'
 'medium_SEC' 'high_SEC']

print(selected_SFM)

3.8. Interaction of variables

Based on the last section we choose features. Let's analyze whether we should include in our model interaction of the features. To realize this goal we use ML approach: CatBoost.

Built samples

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score
DT = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight=None, criterion='gini', max_depth=4,
            max_features='auto', max_leaf_nodes=None,
            min_impurity_decrease=0.0, min_impurity_split=None,
            min_samples_leaf=2, min_samples_split=2,
            min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, presort=False, random_state=250,
            splitter='best')



kfold = KFold(n_splits = 5, shuffle = True, random_state = 250)
DT.fit(X_train, y_train)
kfold_score = cross_val_score(DT, X_train, y_train, cv = kfold)
kfold_score_mean = np.mean(kfold_score)

y_pred_dt = DT.predict(X_test)

y_predict_prob_dt = DT.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

#If we use 0.20 as the cutoff value
target_predict20_dt=[1 if i > 0.20 else 0 for i in y_predict_prob_dt]

5. Conclusions¶

  • We only have 3, highly correlated explanatory variables
  • Jobs that fail have on average larger weight, hence they take more processing time and cost more (overall, not per GB processed)
  • We use Decision Tree to forecast failed jobs (average accuracy score : 0.8142 for test sample)
  • We propose to use the conservative approach with cutoff = 0.2.
  • We have lack information about when exactly the process fails (maybe it happens often at the same time when i.e. 500 GB has been processed?)
  • It would be worth get information about types of data that is processed (text, audio, real-time data / historical data). Maybe different types of files are processed and some of the types are more prone to fail?

From our analysis, we know that the majority of the successful runs have lower amounts of data processed, and lower costs, however, we also noticed that for the most heavy 25% of data, the distinction between successes and failures is not necessarily as significant. We lack additional information on the runs of the pipelines to be able to clearly define the reason for failure. The data batches processed could differ not only in amount of data but also in structure, how complicated aggregations have to be performed, etc.

We observed that the weight has an exponential relationship with runtime and a logarithmic one with cost. This means that the heavier the batch, the runtime increases significantly with each GB. The second important conclusion is that the difference in cost is highly different for the least heavy batches, however, the more data we process, the less impact we have on cost. We lose the majority of the impact at around 80% of our successful pipelines, which is just over 230GBs.

Among the different models featured in this report (CATBoost, Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machine, K-nearest neigbors, Naive Bayes Classifier, Decision Tree, Random Forest, Perceptron, Stochastic Gradient Descent) the Decision Tree has greater accuracy.

We used Decision Tree to forecast failed jobs (average accuracy score : 0.8142 for test sample). Statistical accuracy also refers to statistical significance, meaning that the patterns that have been found in the data have to be valid and not the consequence of noise. In other words, we need to make sure that the model generalizes well and is not overfitted to the train sample.

In the forecast model of possible failed pipeline runs prior to their executions, among the evaluation components, the greatest weight was obtained for one of the basic measures - "MB_data_processed" - amount of MB that have been processed during the pipeline execution.

The statistic for the correctness of detecting failed pipeline runs (sensitivity) is the highest one for Decision Tree in comparison to others technics. From a cautious point of view, we value the low amount of false negative hits over the false positive hits, as the failed pipelines are more costly. We propose to use the conservative approach with cutoff = 0.2.

In order to improve the quality of the model in the future, it is worth considering increasing the number of observations in the data - currently the dataset under consideration covers a relatively small number of observations. Especially when using Machine Learning techniques, more observations are needed.

Additionally, it is worth collecting more information describing the behavior of data transfers between various parts of the companys data storage architecture. It is necessary to identify the so-called strong drivers, which definitely distinguish the result of the ETL process, i.e. 'successful' or 'failed'.

At this stage, we can extract the information that we probably should decrease the amount of data processed per pipeline, by either setting a limit for the batches, or chaning their sizes in the first place. Decreasing the complexity of aggregation and batches could also have positive impact on the amount of data processed in a singular run. We know that we have heavier successful runs, and thats why we can conclude that limiting the amount of data processed is not the only solution and problem to take on.

Appropriate further steps, based on the performed analysis, would be to work with data engineers on extracting additional data and information on the pipeline runs, such that would help us prepare a model with higher predicitive power, and most importantly avoid false negative predictions, as they are the most costly ones. We should also try to work with the data engineers on redesigning the batches (data bricks) to optimise the process. From a wider scope of new information, we could extract additional insights that we are missing at this stage, and understand the process and its outcomes more accurately, which in turn would lead to building a better model in order to optimise the process.

A successful project, that would help us detect possible failed pipeline runs prior to their executions would in turn help to decrease costs, which is the main goal and concern. A possible side effect could be a decrease in runtime of the entire process and decreasing the number of resources required to maintain it.
